<hl>
<seg id=1> Thailand Financial Minister Talin Went to Japan to Talk about the Rescue Loan Issue </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP. Bankok) Thailand Financial Minister Talin went to Japan yesterday to discuss the Thailand's portion from the US$ 30 billion rescue loan (48.6 billion Singapore dollars) that Japan is to offer to save the Asia Economic Community which has been trapped in the financial crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> He said that during his 4-day visit in Japan, he would have in-depth discussions, but he couldn't foresee how much money Japan would promise to give to Thailand. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Talin, in Bangkok International Airport, said to the reporters, "I have reported the outline of utilizing that loan to Prime Minister Chuanlupei, but we haven't decided on the sum, for Japan has not informed us of it yet." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> He said that he hoped to get a low interest rate and generous amortization terms from this program. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> He also said that he would hold separate talks with the officials from the Department of Trade and Industry of Japan, discussing the new aids in support of Thailand's industry and agriculture reconstruction. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The Japanese Financial Minister Miyazawa declared this US$30-billion rescue loan in the Seven Nations Group meeting on October, 10th. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In a short period of time. Japan will allocate US$15 billion in aiding such fields as trade and finance. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Japan will offer direct financial aids by providing loans through Import and Export Bank of Japan and purchasing the Asian public debts, and offer loans in yen to Asian countries for their development aids. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> It will also assure the bank loans of Asian countries and the issuing of Asian bonds, and assist them in international fundraising. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Miyazawa's rescue loan is vitally important to Thailand, for it was not until last month that Thailand postponed its plan to issue the US$0.5 billion global bonds. </seg>
<seg id=12> Thailand wants to use this sum of money to transfuse more flexible capital. </seg>
<seg id=13> The Thai economy is heavily attacked by the high loan costs and the global new markets storm. </seg>
</p>
